<Layout title="Natural Immune System Support">
  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="page-intro intro-box">
    <p><strong>Your immune system</strong> is your body’s defense force — a 24/7 network that fights off viruses, bacteria, and toxins. Our passion for strengthening it began over 20 years ago in Third World countries, where medicine was scarce and lives were on the line. Out of necessity, we searched for natural, effective ways to help the body protect itself. Along the way, we partnered with medical doctors, naturopaths, functional medicine doctors, physical therapists, chiropractors, and other health professionals — combining knowledge, research, and hands-on experience to find lasting ways to improve people’s health. These solutions still guide our work today.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Four Pillars -->
  <div class="grid">
    <section class="card">
      <h2>Cleansing (Detoxification)</h2>
      <p>Cleansing supports your body’s elimination of metabolic waste and environmental toxins that can burden immune function.</p>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>May reduce inflammation burden and improve energy.</li>
        <li>Supports organs of elimination (liver, kidneys, gut, skin).</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="ref">
        <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6163475/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Research: Environmental chemicals &amp; chronic disease (review)</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Liver Support</h2>
      <p>The liver is the body’s primary detox organ, central to immune signaling and antigen clearance.</p>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>Processes xenobiotics, hormones, and inflammatory byproducts.</li>
        <li>Healthy liver function correlates with resilient immunity.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="ref">
        <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7144559/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Research: Liver–immune system interactions (review)</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Antioxidants</h2>
      <p>Antioxidants protect cells from oxidative stress and lipid peroxidation — processes linked to immune dysfunction and chronic disease.</p>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>Dietary antioxidants help neutralize excess free radicals.</li>
        <li>Associated with reduced risk of cardiometabolic and neurodegenerative disease.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="ref">
        <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3249911/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Research: Oxidative stress, antioxidants &amp; disease (review)</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Essential Nutrients</h2>
      <p>Immune cells require steady supplies of vitamins, minerals, amino acids, and healthy fats. Even mild deficiencies can impair defenses.</p>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>Targeted nutrient testing can reveal hidden gaps.</li>
        <li>Correcting deficiencies improves immune competence.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="ref">
        <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fimmu.2018.03160/full" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Frontiers: Immunity &amp; micronutrients (review)</a> ·
        <a href="https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-Consumer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIH ODS: Vitamin D</a> ·
        <a href="https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminC-Consumer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIH ODS: Vitamin C</a> ·
        <a href="https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Zinc-Consumer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIH ODS: Zinc</a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- Root Cause -->
  <section class="highlight-box">
    <h2>Root Cause Medicine</h2>
    <p>Root cause medicine starts with this premise: deficiencies and biochemical bottlenecks often drive disease states. Many people have <em>uptake</em> or <em>processing</em> variants (e.g., methylation, transporters) that limit how well they use certain vitamins and minerals — even with a good diet.</p>
    <ul class="bullets">
      <li><strong>Genetic &amp; functional testing:</strong> identify absorption/activation issues (e.g., B12, folate, vitamin D, zinc, iron).</li>
      <li><strong>Personalized repletion:</strong> fill the specific “holes” first; symptoms often persist until deficiencies are corrected.</li>
      <li><strong>Systems view:</strong> address triggers in gut, hormones, inflammation, sleep, stress, and environment.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="ref">
      <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5421377/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Research: Nutrigenetics &amp; nutrient utilization (review)</a>
    </p>
    <div class="provider-callout">
      <p><strong>Featured Root-Cause Physician:</strong> <a href="https://DanPurserMD.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Dr. Dan Purser (DanPurserMD.com)</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Examples -->
  <section class="examples info-box">
  <h2>Examples of Root Cause &amp; Genetic Testing Physicians</h2>
  <p>If you're exploring root cause genetic testing practitioners, here are a few global and North American examples:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.functional-medicine.associates" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Functional Medicine Associates (London, UK)</a> — Institute for Functional Medicine-certified practitioners offering DNA-based root-cause consultations.</li>
    <li><a href="https://angellongevity.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Angel Longevity Medical Center – Dr. Anju Mathur, MD (Los Angeles, CA, USA)</a> — Board-certified in anti-aging/functional medicine; offers telehealth nationwide.</li>
    <li><a href="https://instituteforfunctionalhealth.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Institute for Functional Health (San Antonio, TX, USA)</a> — Integrative functional medicine clinic using genetics, lifestyle, and environment to personalize care.</li>
    <li><a href="https://www.ifm.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Institute for Functional Medicine (IFM)</a> — Primary U.S. functional medicine educational body; use its "Find a Practitioner" tool to locate clinicians across the country.</li>
  </ul>
